Requirements. Fixed-capacity key-value cache: get(k) returns the value and refreshes recency; put(k,v) inserts or updates, evicting the least recently used entry when a new key would exceed capacity. Both O(1). Generic over K and V. Then: make it safe under concurrent callers and explain how it scales.

Structure. One doubly linked list of (key, value) pairs in recency order, front = most recently used, plus a hash map from key to list iterator. In C++ that is std::list<std::pair<K,V>> and std::unordered_map<K, list iterator>. The load-bearing standard-library fact: std::list iterators remain valid across splice, so order.splice(order.begin(), order, it) moves a node to the front in O(1) with every stored iterator still valid. The list node must store the key redundantly: eviction travels list -> map (pop the tail, then erase the map entry by the tail's key); without the key in the node you cannot erase the map entry, the map holds a dangling iterator keyed by the evicted key, and the next get on it is undefined behavior — the first bug interviewers plant.

Working sketch:
template<class K, class V>
class LRUCache {
  size_t cap;
  std::list<std::pair<K,V>> order; // front = MRU
  std::unordered_map<K, typename std::list<std::pair<K,V>>::iterator> pos;
public:
  explicit LRUCache(size_t c) : cap(c) {}
  std::optional<V> get(const K& k) {
    auto it = pos.find(k);
    if (it == pos.end()) return std::nullopt;
    order.splice(order.begin(), order, it->second);
    return it->second->second;
  }
  void put(const K& k, V v) {
    if (cap == 0) return;
    auto it = pos.find(k);
    if (it != pos.end()) {
      it->second->second = std::move(v);
      order.splice(order.begin(), order, it->second);
      return;
    }
    if (order.size() == cap) { pos.erase(order.back().first); order.pop_back(); }
    order.emplace_front(k, std::move(v));
    pos[k] = order.begin();
  }
};

Traps this sketch already dodges: update-of-existing must refresh recency and must not trigger eviction (size is unchanged); eviction happens only when the key is new; capacity 0; erase-by-stored-key on eviction. Walk one sequence aloud: cap=2, put(1), put(2), get(1), put(3) — key 2 is evicted because get(1) spliced 1 to the front; if your get forgets the splice, 1 dies instead and you fail the question silently.

Design framing. LRU is a data-structure problem wearing an LLD costume — do not invent Node and LinkedList classes when std::list plus splice is the idiomatic O(1) answer; hand-rolled intrusive nodes are justified only after profiling shows allocator pressure. Where OOP genuinely earns a place if asked: an EvictionPolicy strategy to swap LRU/LFU/FIFO behind one cache shell; a loader callback that makes it a read-through cache; a decorator that layers hit/miss statistics without touching the core.

Concurrency. First truth to state: get mutates the list, so every operation is a writer — std::shared_mutex buys exactly nothing here, and saying so preempts the standard follow-up. A single std::mutex guarding both methods is the correct, honest v1. Return V by value (or store shared_ptr<V> and return that): handing out references invites use-after-evict the moment a second thread runs. Scaling under contention is sharding, not cleverer locking: N independent LRUCache shards of capacity C/N, key routed by hash(k) % N, one mutex each — contention drops by roughly N at the cost of per-shard rather than global LRU ordering, which practice accepts (memcached does exactly this). Fine-grained per-node locking of a linked list is a known deadlock-and-race tarpit; name it and decline it.

Follow-ups worth pre-loading: LFU in O(1) is a hashmap plus a doubly linked list of frequency buckets, each bucket holding its own recency list, with a min-frequency pointer for eviction. Redis avoids exact LRU entirely — it samples about five keys and evicts the oldest sampled, trading exactness for zero list maintenance; citing that shows you know approximation is an engineering stance, not a shortcut. TTL bolts on as an expiry timestamp per node checked lazily inside get, with expired entries treated as misses and erased in place.

Requirements. A library-level limiter: bool allow(clientKey); per-client limits; pluggable algorithm with token bucket and sliding window both demanded; thread-safe; millions of client keys; nanosecond-scale hot path. Non-functional core: no clock bugs, no global serialization.

Entities. RateLimiter interface { virtual bool allow(const std::string& key) = 0; virtual ~RateLimiter() = default; }. TokenBucketLimiter and SlidingWindowLimiter implement it — Strategy at the top so a gateway selects per route or per plan. Internally a KeyedStateStore owns a sharded unordered_map from key to per-key state, a factory creating state on first sight, and a TTL sweep for dead keys.

Token bucket math. State per key: { double tokens; steady_clock::time_point last; }. Parameters: capacity B (the burst) and refill rate r tokens/sec. Lazy refill on each call: elapsed = now - last; tokens = min(B, tokens + elapsed * r); last = now; then if tokens >= 1 consume and allow, else reject. No background refill thread — computing refill on demand is fewer moving parts and exactly as correct; the min clamp is what stops an idle key returning with a bucket inflated by hours of sleep.

Sliding window, two flavors. Log: per key a deque of timestamps; on allow, pop-front everything older than now - W, allow iff deque.size() < limit, push now. Exact, but O(limit) memory per key and O(evictions) work. Counter: two adjacent fixed windows with counts; estimate = prevCount * overlapFraction + currCount; allow iff estimate < limit. O(1) memory, small boundary error — the production default at scale. Know both cold; interviewers ask you to compare them unprompted.

C++ sketch:
struct Bucket { double tokens; std::chrono::steady_clock::time_point last; std::mutex m; };
class TokenBucketLimiter : public RateLimiter {
  double cap, rate;
  ShardedMap<std::string, Bucket> buckets; // N shards: each a mutex + unordered_map
public:
  bool allow(const std::string& key) override {
    Bucket& b = buckets.getOrCreate(key, [&]{ return Bucket{cap, std::chrono::steady_clock::now()}; });
    std::lock_guard lg(b.m);
    auto t = std::chrono::steady_clock::now();
    b.tokens = std::min(cap, b.tokens + std::chrono::duration<double>(t - b.last).count() * rate);
    b.last = t;
    if (b.tokens >= 1.0) { b.tokens -= 1.0; return true; }
    return false;
  }
};

Clock choice is load-bearing: steady_clock, never system_clock. Wall time jumps backward under NTP correction — a backward jump mints free tokens or corrupts window eviction; monotonic time cannot go backward. Saying this unprompted is a strong signal.

Concurrency, two layers. Layer 1, the key map: getOrCreate must not race two threads into creating two buckets for one key — shard the map (hash(key) % N shards, each shard a mutex plus unordered_map), do find-or-emplace under the shard lock, and note that node-based unordered_map gives stable references across rehash; never hold the shard lock while doing bucket work. Layer 2, the bucket: a per-bucket mutex serializes refill-plus-consume; the critical section is one duration subtraction, a min, and a compare — nanoseconds. Contention therefore only matters on a single hot key, and the lock-free upgrade for that is a CAS loop over packed {tokens, lastTimestamp} state — mention it, do not implement it. Never one global mutex: it serializes every client on every request, which is the design equivalent of not having written the limiter.

Eviction. Millions of keys means dead buckets accumulate. Sweep each shard periodically, dropping buckets idle longer than max(window, B/r). Safe because a recreated bucket starts full — the error is one free burst for a client who already earned it by being idle.

Flow walkthrough: allow(client-42) -> lock shard hash(client-42)%N, find-or-emplace bucket, unlock shard -> lock bucket, refill from elapsed monotonic time, clamp, consume or reject, unlock. Two short mutexes, zero allocation on the hot path after first sight.

Distributed coda to volunteer: this is per-process; N gateway nodes independently enforcing limit yields N*limit globally. The exact fix is a central store — Redis with a Lua script so read-modify-write of the bucket is atomic server-side; the latency fix is local buckets at limit/N per node, tolerating drift when traffic is skewed across nodes. Name which failure mode each buys before being asked.
